<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Bani Mic — Info.plist additions merged on top of Tauri's default plist.

  Why this file exists in src-tauri/ root:
    Tauri's bundler automatically picks up `Info.plist` next to
    `tauri.conf.json` (see v2.tauri.app/reference/config/#macconfig
    `infoPlist` field doc: "Tauri also looks for a Info.plist file in
    the same directory as the Tauri configuration file").

  Why each key is here:

    NSMicrophoneUsageDescription
      REQUIRED for `navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({audio: true})`
      to work in WKWebView. Without this key, macOS rejects the capture
      request before our UI delegate ever sees it — even if the private
      WKPreferences flag `mediaDevicesEnabled` is on (we set that in
      src/main.rs). The user-facing string here is what shows up in the
      "App would like to access the microphone" system permission
      dialog.

    NSCameraUsageDescription
      Not strictly needed for our app (we only need audio), but
      WKWebView's permission delegate is `requestMediaCapturePermission
      ForOrigin:initiatedByFrame:type:decisionHandler:` which can fire
      with `WKMediaCaptureType.camera` if any future page on the
      sidecar tries video. Including the key with a benign reason
      string is a no-op if no video capture is ever attempted, but
      avoids a TCC crash if it is. Cheaper to declare than to debug.

  NOTE: This plist only takes effect in `cargo tauri build` output
  (i.e., the .app bundle). In `cargo tauri dev` we run the raw
  `target/debug/bani-mic-shell` Mach-O and macOS uses ad-hoc
  permission handling — the runtime KVC flips in src/main.rs are
  what actually expose `navigator.mediaDevices` in dev mode.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>NSMicrophoneUsageDescription</key>
    <string>Bani Mic listens to your singing to identify shabads in real time. Audio is processed entirely on your device — nothing is uploaded.</string>
    <key>NSCameraUsageDescription</key>
    <string>Bani Mic does not currently use the camera, but the WebView reserves this capability for future features.</string>
</dict>
</plist>
